# Keep it simple

Follow the existing folder structure. Add only what is needed for the requested feature. Prefer clarity over cleverness — but **do** apply SOLID and well-chosen [Gang of Four (GoF) design patterns](https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/system-design/gang-of-four-gof-design-patterns/) where they fit naturally.

## SOLID

Apply [SOLID](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SOLID) principles in TypeScript:

- **S — Single Responsibility:** Each class/file has one job (repository = data access, service = business logic, controller = HTTP).
- **O — Open/Closed:** Extend behavior via new implementations (e.g. new strategy, new repository) rather than editing unrelated code.
- **L — Liskov Substitution:** Implementations of an interface must be interchangeable without breaking callers.
- **I — Interface Segregation:** Small, focused interfaces — do not force classes to implement methods they do not use.
- **D — Dependency Inversion:** Depend on **interfaces/abstractions**, not concrete classes. Services receive repositories via constructor injection; controllers receive services the same way.

Use **`interface`** (or abstract classes when justified) for contracts between layers — e.g. `IUserRepository`, `IAuthService`. Concrete implementations live in the matching folder.

## GoF design patterns (use pragmatically)

Reference: [GoF Design Patterns — GeeksforGeeks](https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/system-design/gang-of-four-gof-design-patterns/)

Use patterns **only when they solve a real problem** in this codebase — not every pattern on every feature.

| Pattern | When to use here |
|---------|------------------|
| **Repository** (data access) | All Prisma/database access — already our standard layer |
| **Facade** | Service layer simplifying repository + external API calls for controllers |
| **Strategy** | Payment channel adapters (`IOnlinePaymentAdapter` / Quickpay vs `ITerminalPaymentAdapter` / Verifone POS Cloud); other swappable rules (pricing, payment method) |
| **Factory / Abstract Factory** | Creating the right strategy or payment handler without `if/else` chains |
| **Adapter** | Wrapping external systems (Quickpay, Verifone POS Cloud, webhooks) behind our own interface |
| **Singleton** | Shared app-wide instances only where appropriate (e.g. Prisma client in `infra/db.ts`) |
| **Observer** | Event-style side effects (webhooks, notifications) when decoupling is needed |
| **Decorator** | Adding cross-cutting behavior without modifying core logic (e.g. logging, retry) |

**Creational:** Factory, Singleton — sparingly.  
**Structural:** Adapter, Facade, Repository — most common in this project.  
**Behavioral:** Strategy, Observer, State — when flow or behavior varies by context.

Do **not** introduce patterns that add layers without a clear need (e.g. Mediator, Visitor, Flyweight for CRUD).

## Backend (`Server/src/`)

For each feature, add layers in this order — one concern per file:

1. **Model** — `prisma/schema.prisma` (Prisma models + migration)
2. **Repository** — `repositories/<name>.repository.ts` (implements `I<Name>Repository`; Prisma only)
3. **Service** — `services/<name>.service.ts` (implements `I<Name>Service`; business logic; depends on repository interfaces)
4. **Controller** — `controllers/<name>.controller.ts` (HTTP: parse request, call service interface, send response)
5. **Route** — register in `routes/` (wire method + path to controller)

### Backend rules

- **Routes → controllers → services → repositories → Prisma.** Do not skip layers or call Prisma from controllers.
- Controllers stay thin (no business logic, no direct Prisma).
- Services do not know about Express `req`/`res`.
- One repository per aggregate (e.g. `user.repository.ts`, `order.repository.ts`).
- Define **interfaces** alongside implementations (e.g. `repositories/user.repository.interface.ts` or co-located `IUserRepository` in the same feature folder).
- Do not add microservices, event buses, or generic “BaseService” hierarchies unless explicitly requested.

## Client (`Client/src/app/`)

- **Pages** — `features/<feature>/pages/` (route targets, minimal orchestration)
- **Components** — `features/<feature>/components/` (UI pieces used by pages)
- **Services** — `core/services/` or `features/<feature>/services/` (HTTP calls to the backend only)

### Client rules

- Pages call services; services call `/api/*`. No business logic duplicated from the backend.
- Use **interfaces** for service contracts and typed API responses (from `Shared/types/`).
- No NgRx, signals stores, or state libraries unless explicitly requested.
- No feature modules, shared “utils” folders, or helpers unless needed for the specific task.
- Keep components and pages small and boring.

### Client data & sync (no caching)

- **Do not add caching** — no HTTP caches, service-worker caches, `localStorage`/`sessionStorage` for API data, TanStack Query cache layers, or similar. Caching causes stale/out-of-sync UI; we are not using it yet.
- **After POST/PUT/PATCH success:** update client state from the **response body** returned by the server (append to a list, replace one item, patch fields in a signal/store). Do **not** refetch the full list or reload the page unless explicitly requested or the response is insufficient.
- **GET** loads data when a page opens; **mutations** trust the server response as the source of truth for what changed.
- Backend: do not add Redis or response caching unless explicitly requested.

### Pagination & lazy loading (always)

Use **automated pagination** and **lazy loading** for every list or collection — never load unbounded datasets.

**Backend**

- All list endpoints accept pagination params (e.g. `page` + `limit`, or `cursor` + `limit`) and return a **paginated envelope** (items + `total` / `hasMore` / `nextCursor`).
- Repositories/services use Prisma `skip`/`take` or cursor-based queries — never `findMany()` without a limit on user-facing lists.
- Define default page size (e.g. 20) and enforce a max limit.
- Shared shape in `Shared/types/` (e.g. `PaginatedResponse<T>`).

**Client**

- **Lazy load:** fetch the first page when a page/view opens; load the next page when the user scrolls near the end, clicks “Load more”, or equivalent — do not request all rows upfront.
- **Append** new pages to existing in-memory list state (do not replace the full list on page 2+ unless refreshing).
- After a successful **POST**, add the returned item to the current list if it belongs on screen — do not refetch all pages.
- List services accept page/cursor params and return the shared paginated type.

**Do not** implement unpaginated “get all” APIs or client calls except for tiny fixed sets (e.g. enum-like config) explicitly approved.

## Shared types (`Shared/types/`)

- API request/response shapes and domain types used by **both** client and server live in `Shared/types/`.
- Define each type **once**; import from `Shared/` in Server and Client.
- Do not duplicate DTO interfaces in `Client` and `Server` separately.
- Server may use Zod (or similar) for validation, but the **shape** should match the shared type.
- Define request/response types in `Shared/types/` **before** implementing a new endpoint.

## Security & tenancy

**Multi-tenant payment isolation and cross-tenant access rules:** see **`tenant-security.mdc`** (always apply).

- **`tenant_id` on every tenant-scoped query** — resolve tenant from JWT or slug; never trust `tenantId` from the client body alone.
- **Auth:** hash passwords (bcrypt/argon2); never return `passwordHash`; protect `/admin` and `/kasse` with JWT + role guards.
- **Validate all API input** with Zod (or similar) — shared types describe shape; validation enforces it.
- **Rate-limit** login and other sensitive endpoints.
- **Quickpay / Verifone:** API keys and private keys **server-only**; never store raw card data; never log secrets or PANs.
- **Consistent API errors** — e.g. `{ error: string }` with correct HTTP status (400, 401, 403, 409, 500); do not leak stack traces to clients.

## Payments & async

**Always consult `payment-setup.mdc` before implementing payment, checkout, webhook, or terminal code** — online via [Quickpay](https://learn.quickpay.net/tech-talk/), in-store via [Verifone POS Cloud](https://docs.verifone.com/pos-cloud).

- **Webhooks:** verify signature → persist event → return 200 quickly → process in a worker/queue.
- **Idempotency** on payments and webhooks — duplicate events must not double-charge or duplicate side effects.
- **Payment state machine** — e.g. `created → authorized → captured → failed / refunded`; transitions are explicit.
- **Queues for async work** (webhooks, receipts, retries) are allowed — distinct from HTTP/Redis **caching**, which we avoid for now.
- Use **Prisma transactions** when updating multiple related records (order + payment + inventory).

## Data & API conventions

- **Timestamps** (`createdAt`, `updatedAt`) on business tables.
- **Sort/filter** query params alongside pagination on list endpoints.
- Prefer **`/api/v1/...`** if the API may serve external or mobile clients long-term.
- Define **soft delete vs hard delete** and GDPR export/delete per tenant when handling merchant data.

## Client (auth & UX without design)

- **Auth interceptor** — attach Bearer token to API calls.
- **Route guards** — restrict `/admin` and `/kasse` to authenticated staff.
- **Loading, error, and empty states** on lists and forms — minimal markup only (no styling unless asked).
- Prefer **server response as truth** after mutations; avoid optimistic UI for payment flows unless explicitly requested.
- **Lazy-load Angular feature routes** (`loadComponent`) where it keeps bundles small.

## DevOps & quality

- **Never commit `.env`** — use `.env.example` for documentation only.
- **Review Prisma migration SQL** before applying; use `prisma migrate dev`, not ad-hoc schema drift.
- Run **`prisma generate`** after schema changes (CI/postinstall when applicable).
- **Structured logging** and a **correlation id** per request for tracing payment issues.
- **Tests** for tenant isolation, auth, and critical payment paths — at least integration tests on happy and error paths.

## EU / compliance (always EU)

- **GDPR:** ability to export/delete a tenant’s data; EU-appropriate hosting and retention policy.
- **PSD2 / 3DS:** handle SCA in the single shared checkout module (`features/checkout`).
- **Audit log** for payment, refund, and merchant-setting changes (who, when, what).

## Process

- **One feature = one vertical slice:** schema → repository → service → controller → route → shared types → client service → page.

## General

- Implement only what was asked — no speculative features, refactors, or “while we’re here” changes.
- Match naming and style of neighboring files in the same layer.
- **Simple first:** one clear class per layer beats a pattern applied for its own sake.
- When a GoF pattern fits (see table above), use it with an interface so the code stays testable and swappable.